## Subnetting

### Subnet Mask Binary
- /24: 255.255.255.0 = 11111111.11111111.11111111.00000000
- /16: 255.255.0.0 = 11111111.11111111.00000000.00000000
- /8: 255.0.0.0 = 11111111.00000000.00000000.00000000

### Subnet Calculation Formula
- Number of subnets = 2^(borrowed bits)
- Number of hosts = 2^(host bits) - 2

---

## MAC Addresses

### Structure
- 48 bits = 12 hexadecimal characters
- Format: AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF
- First 3 octets: OUI (manufacturer identifier)
- Last 3 octets: NIC-specific (unique to device)

### Known OUIs
| OUI | Manufacturer |
|-----|--------------|
| 00:1A:2B | Dell |
| AC:BC:32 | Apple |
| 00:14:22 | Toshiba |
| 00:50:56 | VMware |

---

## ARP (Address Resolution Protocol)

### Purpose
Resolves IP addresses to MAC addresses on local network

### ARP Process
1. Device broadcasts: "Who has IP 192.168.1.1?"
2. Router replies: "I have 192.168.1.1, my MAC is 11:22:33:44:55:66"
3. Device stores in ARP cache

### ARP Commands








View ARP cache
arp -a

Add static ARP entry
arp -s 192.168.1.1 11:22:33:44:55:66

Delete ARP entry
arp -d 192.168.1.1

text

